# On our way back home - Solution

Let's make request to RSS url to get feeds [http://cyber-ctf.be.s3-website-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/rss](http://cyber-ctf.be.s3-website-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/rss):

![rss.JPG](images/rss.JPG)

As we can see we get the following XML response:
```xml
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<rss xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" version="2.0">
   <channel>
      <title>CyberArk Innovation challenge 4</title>
      <link>https://www.cyberark.com</link>
      <description>RSS feed for: CyberArk Innovation</description>
      <language>en-EN</language>
      <lastBuildDate>Tue, 20 Jul 2021 18:30:19 GMT</lastBuildDate>
      <generator>rfeed v1.1.1</generator>
      <docs>https://github.com/svpino/rfeed/blob/master/README.md</docs>
      <item>
         <title>CyberArk's spaceship</title>
         <description>Coming home</description>
         <author>CyberArk Innovation</author>
         <pubDate>Tue, 20 Jul 2021 18:30:19 GMT</pubDate>
      </item>
      <item>
         <title>puzzle</title>
         <link>https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cyber-ctf.be/chl4/q.txt</link>
         <author>CyberArk Innovation</author>
         <pubDate>Tue, 20 Jul 2021 18:30:19 GMT</pubDate>
      </item>
   </channel>
</rss>
```

```<link>``` attribute contains the following url [https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cyber-ctf.be/chl4/q.txt](https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cyber-ctf.be/chl4/r.txt) which is:
```

```

![q.png](images/q.png)

We can see it's part of QRCode.

If we are trying to get more feeds we get the following response:

Which [https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cyber-ctf.be/chl4/r.txt](https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cyber-ctf.be/chl4/r.txt) is:
```

```

If we contat the base64 from q.txt with r.txt we get the following image:

![qr.png](images/qr.png)

And more feeds will give us link of [https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cyber-ctf.be/chl4/c.txt](https://s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cyber-ctf.be/chl4/c.txt):
```

```

So by contace ***q***.txt,***r***.txt,***c***.txt we get the final QRCode:

![qrc.png](images/qrc.png)

This result of the [QRCode](https://webqr.com/) is:
```
https://bitbucket.org/space-expedition/expedition/src/master/, AKIA5FNOHSTOQECIOTPZ, S/UmZqK5bEl8edYiUtQqBKzanqMhtHOBbSDzj6GM
```

By observing the URL [https://bitbucket.org/space-expedition/expedition/src/master/](https://bitbucket.org/space-expedition/expedition/src/master/) we can see the following bitbucket repo:
![bitbucket.JPG](images/bitbucket.JPG)

By observing the file [https://bitbucket.org/space-expedition/expedition/src/master/bitbucket-pipelines.yml](https://bitbucket.org/space-expedition/expedition/src/master/bitbucket-pipelines.yml) we get:
```yaml
image:
  name: 904992888029.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wayhome:latest
  aws:
    access-key: $AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID
    secret-key: $AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
pipelines:
  default:
    - step:
        script:
          - echo 'note to myself - don’t spill coffee on spaceship parts'
```

So as we can see it's pull an image (```904992888029.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wayhome:latest```) from containar registry (hosted by amazon) with ```access-key: $AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID```, ```secret-key: $AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY```.

If we read about AWS keys on [https://summitroute.com/blog/2018/06/20/aws_security_credential_formats/](https://summitroute.com/blog/2018/06/20/aws_security_credential_formats/) we can see that:

![access.JPG](images/access.JPG)

![secret.JPG](images/secret.JPG)

Actually those keys looks exactly like our keys (from QR code):
```
AKIA5FNOHSTOQECIOTPZ - Possible the $AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID
S/UmZqK5bEl8edYiUtQqBKzanqMhtHOBbSDzj6GM - Possible the $AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY
```

We can see also the bitbucket pipeline execute script on images.

So our target is to make exactly the same things like the yaml does.

We need to create a bitbucket [repository](https://support.atlassian.com/bitbucket-cloud/docs/create-a-repository/) with the following [pipeline](https://support.atlassian.com/bitbucket-cloud/docs/get-started-with-bitbucket-pipelines/) (We need to make Two-step verification on bitbucket for that):
```yaml
image:
  name: 904992888029.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wayhome:latest
  aws:
    access-key: AKIA5FNOHSTOQECIOTPZ
    secret-key: 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
pipelines:
  default:
    - step:
        script:
          - echo 'Run on 904992888029.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wayhome:latest image'
          - ls /
```

By running the pipeline we can see:

![pipeline.JPG](images/pipeline.JPG)

We can see the ```earth``` directory, Let's observe it by changing the yaml to (The pipleline running automatically after commit):
```yaml
image:
  name: 904992888029.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wayhome:latest
  aws:
    access-key: AKIA5FNOHSTOQECIOTPZ
    secret-key: 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
pipelines:
  default:
    - step:
        script:
          - ls /earth
```

And we can see it's contains file ```coords.txt.gpg```, Let's get this file by:
```yaml
image:
  name: 904992888029.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wayhome:latest
  aws:
    access-key: AKIA5FNOHSTOQECIOTPZ
    secret-key: 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
pipelines:
  default:
    - step:
        script:
          - base64 -w0 /earth/coords.txt.gpg
```

We get the following base64 for this gpg file:
```
jA0EAwMCKqiAW+S2XdFgyUa8oEciOzyuWNq/hwi7KlNcBikLuLM7X1vV9d41mAjiZURnDV2Qk+Pjl6vZt7SEo9K4xda8TgYUu3qWgsAKx8jODZn0LfDd
```

By converting this base64 to file we can see it's a gpg file as expected:
```console
┌─[evyatar@parrot]─[/cyberark/innovation/on_our_back_home]
└──╼$ echo "jA0EAwMCKqiAW+S2XdFgyUa8oEciOzyuWNq/hwi7KlNcBikLuLM7X1vV9d41mAjiZURnDV2Qk+Pjl6vZt7SEo9K4xda8TgYUu3qWgsAKx8jODZn0LfDd" | base64 -d > coords.txt.gpg
┌─[evyatar@parrot]─[/cyberark/innovation/on_our_back_home]
└──╼$ file coords.txt.gpg 
coords.txt.gpg: GPG symmetrically encrypted data (CAST5 cipher)
```

We need password to decode it, We can get it from enviornment variables as follow:
```yaml
image:
  name: 904992888029.dkr.ecr.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/wayhome:latest
  aws:
    access-key: AKIA5FNOHSTOQECIOTPZ
    secret-key: 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
pipelines:
  default:
    - step:
        script:
          - env
```

As we can see we get the password ```PASS=wDmL7uC3H8FTr3vS``` (Full yaml avaliable on [bitbucket-pipelines.yml](bitbucket-pipelines.yml)):

![password.JPG](images/password.JPG)

And finally we can decrypt the gpg file:
```console
┌─[evyatar@parrot]─[/cyberark/innovation/on_our_back_home]
└──╼$ gpg -d coords.txt.gpg
<Enter wDmL7uC3H8FTr3vS as password>
gpg: CAST5 encrypted data
gpg: encrypted with 1 passphrase
28.49662233341438, -80.54938494992965
gpg: WARNING: message was not integrity protected
gpg: Hint: If this message was created before the year 2003 it is
     likely that this message is legitimate.  This is because back
     then integrity protection was not widely used.
gpg: Use the option '--ignore-mdc-error' to decrypt anyway.
gpg: decryption forced to fail!

```

And we get the following coordinates ```28.49662233341438, -80.54938494992965``` (Which not worked as flag).

By converting the coordinates to location using [Google Maps](https://www.google.cm/maps/place/28%C2%B029'47.8%22N+80%C2%B032'57.8%22W/@28.4966223,-80.5515736,17z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d28.4966223!4d-80.5493849) we get the location:

![launch.JPG](images/launch.JPG)

And the flag is ```Launch Complex 15```.
